{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480332"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:41:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:41:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"41"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/41"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.12,0.47,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"41"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85394"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/41"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"41"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69681"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2038"},{"type":"tags","id":"3511"},{"type":"tags","id":"4727"},{"type":"tags","id":"4728"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12320"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29318"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44609"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85394"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a 12-month history of erectile dysfunction. He has been unable to initiate and maintain an erection with sexual stimulation, and for the past six months has been unable to achieve an erection at all. He reports generalised fatigue and difficulty concentrating. His medical history includes stable angina, type 2 diabetes mellitus and hyperlipidaemia. His current medications include aspirin, rosuvastatin and metformin. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history and drinks about three glasses of wine a night. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His BMI is 29 kg/m2. He has dense facial hair and his testicular volume is 14cc. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to appropriate lifestyle interventions, which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral pseudoephedrine","Topical testosterone gel","Oral tadalafil","Vacuum erectile device","Intracavernosal alprostadil"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EErectile dysfunction (ED) is common and often under-reported, with a prevalence of over 60% in some surveys. The most appropriate initial pharmacological management for this patient is \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral tadalafil\u003C/strong\u003E, a phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitor (PDE5i). PDE5 inhibitors are considered first-line pharmacological therapy for ED due to their efficacy, ease of use, and generally favourable side effect profile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical testosterone gel\u003C/strong\u003E is not the first-line treatment for ED. While testosterone deficiency can contribute to ED, there is no indication of hypogonadism in this patient\u0027s presentation. His symptoms of fatigue and poor concentration could be features of hypogonadism however they are non-specific and the otherwise has normal facial hair and testicular volume. Testosterone replacement should only be considered after confirming low testosterone levels and ruling out contraindications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral pseudoephedrine\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for ED treatment. It is sometimes used for retrograde ejaculation but has no role in managing erectile dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVacuum erectile devices\u003C/strong\u003E can be effective for ED but are typically considered second-line therapy after oral medications have been tried or if they are contraindicated. They require more effort to use and may be less appealing to patients compared to oral medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracavernosal alprostadil\u003C/strong\u003E (prostaglandin E1) injections are also effective but are usually reserved for patients who do not respond to or cannot use oral medications. They are more invasive and can be associated with pain at the injection site.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that while pharmacological management is important, addressing lifestyle factors is crucial. This patient would benefit from smoking cessation, reducing alcohol intake, weight loss, and better management of his diabetes and cardiovascular risk factors. These lifestyle modifications can improve erectile function and overall health.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELastly, it is worth noting that PDE5 inhibitors like tadalafil are contraindicated in patients taking nitrates due to the risk of severe hypotension. However, this patient is not reported to be on nitrates for his stable angina, making tadalafil a safe option. Always ensure there are no contraindications before prescribing PDE5 inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitors are considered first-line pharmacological therapy for erectile dysfunction","The use of phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitors is contraindicated in patients taking nitrates due to the risk of severe hypotension"],"references":["McMahon CG, Current diagnosis and management of erectile dysfunction. Med J Aust. 2019 Jun;210(10):469-476.","Irwin G M, Erectile dysfunction. Prim Care Clin Office Pract 2019; 46:249-55."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69681"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"41"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69681"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-16T14:19:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-16T14:21:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"41"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85394"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com